# Prefer Direct JavaScript

- Do not add defensive guards for values that are expected by normal control flow.
- Write the straightforward version first when the data shape is already required by the feature.
- Avoid stacking optional chaining, `Array.isArray`, fallback arrays/objects, or nullish defaults just to "be safe."

## Default Approach

- Prefer short, direct code that is easy to read in one pass.
- If invalid input is possible and important, fail clearly instead of silently masking it.
- Do not add TypeScript-like runtime protection patterns to regular JavaScript unless explicitly requested.

## Example

```javascript
// Avoid over-protective style
const startupCabs = Array.isArray(rollingStock?.trains)
  ? rollingStock.trains.map((train) => train?.DCC_ID)
  : [];

// Prefer direct and clear style
const startupCabs = rollingStock.trains.map((train) => train.DCC_ID);
```
